1. Definition and behavior
for...of iterates over the values produced by an object's default iterator (its @@iterator method). It yields values (not keys) and is intended for iterables: arrays, strings, Maps, Sets, generators, TypedArrays, and user-defined iterables.

2. Normalised extract (implementation details)
- Syntax: for (var variable of iterable) statement
- Evaluation steps (simplified):
  - Retrieve iterator = iterable[Symbol.iterator]()
  - Loop: let result = iterator.next(); if result.done is true, exit loop; else assign result.value to loop variable and execute body.
- For strings: iteration yields complete characters (Unicode code points), handling surrogate pairs as single iteration values.
- For Map: default iterator produces entries [key, value]; for (const [k,v] of map) destructuring extracts both.

3. Iterable protocol and method resolution
- An object is iterable if it has a function at the key Symbol.iterator.
- Custom iterables must implement a next() method returning { value: any, done: boolean }.
- The for...of construct does not iterate object property names (use for...in for keys) and does not expose the iterator object unless explicitly captured.

4. Performance and common patterns
- Use for...of when you need actual values and when the iterable implements a native fast iterator (arrays, typed arrays).
- To iterate numeric ranges, prefer for (let i=0;i<n;i++) for performance-critical loops; for...of adds iterator overhead.
- Use break/continue/return inside loop body as usual; 'continue' proceeds to next iterator.next() call.

5. Troubleshooting and gotchas
- Do not use for...of on plain objects (Object.prototype has no default iterator) — it will throw a TypeError; use Object.keys() or Object.entries() instead.
- When modifying the iterable during iteration, behavior depends on the iterator implementation; arrays' built-in iterators reflect modifications to the array made before the next next() call in many engines but avoid relying on this.

